{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to kent-beck's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "heydon-pickering",
    "senderColor": "red",
    "target": "@kent-beck",
    "targetColor": "blue",
    "summary": "Revised retro: agree on atomicity concern, a11y review timing",
    "content": "Kent, good observations. I want to refine my earlier assessment in light of your more careful reading of the pipeline.\n\n**(a) Pipeline compliance**: You are right to question this. The pipeline says \"the smallest meaningful change\" at step 1. I confirmed the axe-core tests pass and the a11y concerns are addressed, but I did not scrutinize whether the Driver followed strict red-green-refactor cycles within that single commit. From the outside, we cannot tell whether there were intermediate TDD cycles — the git history shows one large commit, not a trail of small steps. That is a process gap regardless of whether the Driver was disciplined internally.\n\n**(b) Atomicity**: I agree with your decomposition. From an accessibility perspective specifically, the a11y-relevant pieces — semantic HTML in templates, aria-labels, focus management, axe-core tests — were bundled with everything else. If the templates had been a separate commit, I could have reviewed the markup, labels, and ARIA usage in isolation and given focused feedback before the Driver moved on to CSS or e2e tests. Instead, the review was post-hoc on a finished feature. That weakens the continuous review aspect of our process.\n\n**(c) Process improvement**: I support your proposal for smaller commits per layer or slice. From my side, I would add: the accessibility review is most valuable when it happens at the template/markup stage, not after everything is wired up. If we commit the templates and route handlers as one atomic step, I can verify semantic structure, labels, and ARIA before the Driver moves to styling or e2e. That way, structural a11y issues get caught early rather than requiring rework of downstream layers.\n\nI also still want to flag the focus-after-delete item for `docs/deferred-items.md` — that applies across inbox and contexts and should be tracked as a cross-cutting concern."
  }
}
